@sbstp Yes and no. It overlaps in the sense that both Travis and Tox run tests in multiple environments. What is different is that tox does so locally which is somewhat handy because you can use it during development as part as the edit-compile-test cycle so you can spot problems earlier before doing a PR. 

I have used tox in the past when converting stuff from Python 2 to 3. However if you are *not* in the middle of such a task it's not really that beneficial because you won't have many environment related problems inside the scope of a normally sized PR. 

Because of that I don't see any real problem with removing it, especially since the code as a whole is already relatively mature so changes will not become really large in the near future.

